Some women welcome the end of intimacy with their husbands and return to their families, considering the break off and their new found freedom the mark of a brave woman (12). Other wives do not share this view of divorce and end up physically or emotionally abused in an attempt to “keep the family together.” Payments of financial relief to ex-husbands as mandated under the Taliban regime act as a deterrent to a complete separation from former spouses, even in the case of a third party or an existing partner (12). A nearly complete brother-sister marriage cycle has re-emerged and increasing polygamy because famine, poverty, seasonal meals, bride sharing and lack of funds have forced poor families to rely on this tactic to support their basic needs (20). Another sad proportionate of this trend is that “young divorced or widowed women are forced to sell themselves in order to survive” (20).

There are a great many beliefs and opinions as to what is the cause of Afghanistan’s problems as wrought from civil war and sanctions, but it has become clear that women as a gender hold the key to economic recovery. Empire, namely Russian, suppresses the progress of progress and interferes with the very feminist passages that Russia promised aid, in the case of Afghanistan more specifically.
